05668nam a22007815i 9780674736153DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979910260  a(OCoLC)984644168  a(OCoLC)987949247  a(OCoLC)992490054  a(OCoLC)999367044  a97806747361537 a10.4159/harvard.97806747361532doi  a(DE-B1597)427425  a(OCoLC)897600385  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aPHI0010002bisacsh04a101223  aCC 11002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17603:1 aRodowick, D. N., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPhilosophy's Artful Conversation /cD. N. Rodowick. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2015] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (330 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIn Place of Beginning Again -- t1. A Permanent State of Suspension or Deferment -- t2. How Theory Became History -- t3. “Philosophy is not one of the natural sciences” -- t4 “I will teach you diff erences” -- t5. An Assembling of Reminders -- t6. “... a complicated network of similarities overlapping and criss- crossing” -- t7. Gedankenwegen: On Import and Interpretation -- t8. “Of which we cannot speak ...”: Philosophy and the Humanities -- t9. What is (Film) Philosophy? -- t10. Order Out of Chaos -- t11. Idea, Image, and Intuition -- t12. The World, Time -- t13. The Ordinary Necessity of Philosophy -- t14. “Art now exists in the condition of philosophy” -- t15. Falling in Love with the World -- t16. Ontology and Desire, or a Moving Response to Skepticism -- t17. Automatism and the Declaration of Existence in Time -- t18. Ethical Practices of the Ordinary -- t19. Perfectionism as Self- Disobedience -- t20. Comedy and Community -- t21. A Digression on Difference and Interpretation -- t22. Perfectionism’s Ironic Transport -- t23. An Elegy for Theory -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTheory has been an embattled discourse in the academy for decades. But now it faces a serious challenge from those who want to model the analytical methods of all scholarly disciplines on the natural sciences. What is urgently needed, says D. N. Rodowick, is a revitalized concept of theory that can assess the limits of scientific explanation and defend the unique character of humanistic understanding. Philosophy’s Artful Conversation is a timely and searching examination of theory’s role in the arts and humanities today. Expanding the insights of his earlier book, Elegy for Theory, and drawing on the diverse thought of Ludwig Wittgenstein, G. H. von Wright, P. M. S. Hacker, Richard Rorty, and Charles Taylor, Rodowick provides a blueprint of what he calls a “philosophy of the humanities.” In a surprising and illuminating turn, he views the historical emergence of theory through the lens of film theory, arguing that aesthetics, literary studies, and cinema studies cannot be separated where questions of theory are concerned. These discourses comprise a conceptual whole, providing an overarching model of critique that resembles, in embryonic form, what a new philosophy of the humanities might look like. Rodowick offers original readings of Gilles Deleuze and Stanley Cavell, bringing forward unexamined points of contact between two thinkers who associate philosophical expression with film and the arts. A major contribution to cross-disciplinary intellectual history, Philosophy’s Artful Conversation reveals the many threads connecting the arts and humanities with the history of philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPhilosophy, Modernx21st century. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny21st century. 0aTheory (Philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisac